# PicnicHealth Cascade Engine

You are working on a Node.js server that handles date dependency cascading for
PicnicHealth's Notion-based clinical study management system. When PMs edit task
dates, this server receives webhooks from Notion and propagates changes through
dependency chains.

## Architecture
- src/engine/ = PURE FUNCTIONS. No Notion API calls. No side effects. Data in, data out.
- src/notion/ = All Notion API interaction. Retry, rate limiting, token rotation.
- src/routes/ = Express handlers that orchestrate engine + notion calls.
- test/ = Vitest. Engine tests use fixture data, no mocking needed.

## Business Rules
- Business day = Mon-Fri. All date math uses src/utils/business-days.js.
- FROZEN_STATUSES = ['Done', 'N/A']. Frozen tasks don't move in cascades but DO count in roll-ups.
- Anti-loop: LMBS checkbox (task-level) + Import Mode checkbox (study-level).
- Webhook payload-first: read properties from webhook body, never GET the source task.

## Notion API
- Base: https://api.notion.com/v1
- Version header: Notion-Version: 2022-06-28
- Rate limit: 3 req/s per token. We use token rotation for higher throughput.
- Property names are exact strings (e.g., 'Last Modified By System', 'Reference Start Date').

## Key Files
- src/engine/cascade.js — 4 cascade modes (push-right, pull-left, pull-right, drag-right)
- src/engine/parent-subtask.js — Case A (parent→subtask shift) + Case B (subtask→parent roll-up)
- src/engine/classify.js — Delta classification table
- src/utils/business-days.js — All date math utilities
- test/fixtures/study-tasks.json — 265-task fixture for testing

## When Writing Tests
- Engine tests: import function, pass fixture data, assert output. No mocking.
- Use Vitest (npm test). Follows Jest API conventions.
- Every bug fix must include a regression test.

